WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.000
[Guest]: I-V-M

00:00:30.000 --> 00:00:32.000
[Amit Varma]: And humans for even longer than that.

00:00:32.000 --> 00:00:34.000
[Amit Varma]: It seems short-sighted to make

00:00:34.000 --> 00:00:36.000
[Amit Varma]: that nation-state the focus of our identity.

00:00:36.000 --> 00:00:38.000
[Amit Varma]: And it's equally short-sighted,

00:00:38.000 --> 00:00:40.000
[Amit Varma]: in fact, to base our identity

00:00:40.000 --> 00:00:42.000
[Amit Varma]: on any other circumstance of

00:00:42.000 --> 00:00:44.000
[Amit Varma]: our birth, like our ethnicity

00:00:44.000 --> 00:00:46.000
[Amit Varma]: or religion or caste.

00:00:46.000 --> 00:00:48.000
[Amit Varma]: Those also haven't been around for too long

00:00:48.000 --> 00:00:50.000
[Amit Varma]: and are far more fluid than we realize.

00:00:50.000 --> 00:00:52.000
[Amit Varma]: If you think of your identity

00:00:52.000 --> 00:00:54.000
[Amit Varma]: as an atomized individual

00:00:54.000 --> 00:00:56.000
[Amit Varma]: who is a product of chance and circumstance,

00:00:56.000 --> 00:00:58.000
[Amit Varma]: that's part of the truth right there.

00:00:58.000 --> 00:01:00.000
[Amit Varma]: But if you see yourself also as

00:01:00.000 --> 00:01:02.000
[Amit Varma]: connected to the past, a small part

00:01:02.000 --> 00:01:04.000
[Amit Varma]: of something much bigger and older

00:01:04.000 --> 00:01:06.000
[Amit Varma]: than yourself, then you need to go

00:01:06.000 --> 00:01:08.000
[Amit Varma]: a little further back

00:01:08.000 --> 00:01:10.000
[Amit Varma]: than 70 years, or a few

00:01:10.000 --> 00:01:12.000
[Amit Varma]: hundred years, or even

00:01:12.000 --> 00:01:14.000
[Amit Varma]: a few thousand years.

00:01:14.000 --> 00:01:16.000
[Amit Varma]: You need to read Tony Joseph's book,

00:01:16.000 --> 00:01:18.000
[Amit Varma]: Early Indians.

00:01:20.000 --> 00:01:22.000
[Unknown]: Welcome to The Seen and The Unseen,

00:01:22.000 --> 00:01:24.000
[Unknown]: our weekly podcast on economics,

00:01:24.000 --> 00:01:26.000
[Unknown]: politics, and behavioral science.

00:01:26.000 --> 00:01:28.000
[Unknown]: Please welcome your host, Amit

00:01:28.000 --> 00:01:30.000
[Amit Varma]: Badma.

00:01:30.000 --> 00:01:32.000
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to The Seen and The Unseen. I've spoken

00:01:32.000 --> 00:01:34.000
[Amit Varma]: to historians on the show before and chatted

00:01:34.000 --> 00:01:36.000
[Amit Varma]: about history, but the furthest back I've

00:01:36.000 --> 00:01:38.000
[Amit Varma]: gone is a few hundred years. My

00:01:38.000 --> 00:01:40.000
[Amit Varma]: guest today, the author Tony Joseph, will

00:01:40.000 --> 00:01:42.000
[Amit Varma]: take us back tens of thousands of

00:01:42.000 --> 00:01:44.000
[Amit Varma]: years. Early Indians is

00:01:44.000 --> 00:01:46.000
[Amit Varma]: a book that answers many important questions

00:01:46.000 --> 00:01:48.000
[Amit Varma]: about our species, particularly our species

00:01:48.000 --> 00:01:50.000
[Amit Varma]: in India. Where did humans

00:01:50.000 --> 00:01:52.000
[Amit Varma]: come from? When did they get to India?

00:01:52.000 --> 00:01:54.000
[Amit Varma]: Who are the original Indians, if such

00:01:54.000 --> 00:01:56.000
[Amit Varma]: a term applies? Who were the Harappans?

00:01:56.000 --> 00:01:58.000
[Amit Varma]: Who were the Aryans?

00:01:58.000 --> 00:02:00.000
[Amit Varma]: Whose descendants are we? Are

00:02:00.000 --> 00:02:02.000
[Amit Varma]: North Indians and South Indians different from

00:02:02.000 --> 00:02:04.000
[Amit Varma]: each other in some fundamental way?

00:02:04.000 --> 00:02:06.000
[Amit Varma]: Are tribals lesser than our city

00:02:06.000 --> 00:02:08.000
[Amit Varma]: dwellers? Some of these

00:02:08.000 --> 00:02:10.000
[Amit Varma]: are questions of politics, but

00:02:10.000 --> 00:02:12.000
[Amit Varma]: all of them can be answered only by science.

00:02:12.000 --> 00:02:14.000
[Amit Varma]: And in the last few years,

00:02:14.000 --> 00:02:16.000
[Amit Varma]: literally in this decade, there have

00:02:16.000 --> 00:02:18.000
[Amit Varma]: been radical advances in a number

00:02:18.000 --> 00:02:20.000
[Amit Varma]: of sciences that now answer

00:02:20.000 --> 00:02:22.000
[Amit Varma]: these contentious questions.

00:02:22.000 --> 00:02:24.000
[Amit Varma]: And Tony's remarkable book

00:02:24.000 --> 00:02:26.000
[Amit Varma]: reveals all. As does this

00:02:26.000 --> 00:02:28.000
[Amit Varma]: episode, so keep listening. I'll begin

