[Guest]: and it is absolutely amazing

00:05:06.000 --> 00:05:08.000
[Guest]: experience. I think the

00:05:08.000 --> 00:05:10.000
[Guest]: people that I worked with in business standard and later

00:05:10.000 --> 00:05:12.000
[Guest]: on in business world also and

00:05:12.000 --> 00:05:14.000
[Guest]: those were really

00:05:14.000 --> 00:05:16.000
[Guest]: outstanding teams and a pleasure to work with.

00:05:16.000 --> 00:05:18.000
[Amit Varma]: When did you actually start as a journalist?

00:05:18.000 --> 00:05:20.000
[Amit Varma]: What brought you into journalism?

00:05:20.000 --> 00:05:22.000
[Amit Varma]: You know when I was growing up in the 80s

00:05:22.000 --> 00:05:24.000
[Amit Varma]: the common view about journalists is

00:05:24.000 --> 00:05:26.000
[Amit Varma]: that they failed at everything else.

00:05:26.000 --> 00:05:28.000
[Amit Varma]: They didn't become an engineer or a doctor.

00:05:28.000 --> 00:05:30.000
[Guest]: What brought you into journalism?

00:05:30.000 --> 00:05:32.000
[Guest]: Journalism has always been

00:05:32.000 --> 00:05:34.000
[Guest]: what shall I say, an attraction

00:05:34.000 --> 00:05:36.000
[Guest]: for me because I think the

00:05:36.000 --> 00:05:38.000
[Guest]: idea of engaging with public ideas

00:05:38.000 --> 00:05:40.000
[Guest]: or public mind

00:05:40.000 --> 00:05:42.000
[Guest]: has been exciting. So the place

00:05:42.000 --> 00:05:44.000
[Guest]: that I joined us for first was a

00:05:44.000 --> 00:05:46.000
[Guest]: newspaper called Newstime. It was a

00:05:46.000 --> 00:05:48.000
[Guest]: newspaper that was began for the first time by the

00:05:48.000 --> 00:05:50.000
[Guest]: Inado group in Hyderabad. Which year?

00:05:50.000 --> 00:05:52.000
[Guest]: This would be 1983.

00:05:52.000 --> 00:05:54.000
[Guest]: Right. I would have been all

00:05:54.000 --> 00:05:56.000
[Guest]: of 21 years old. Right.

00:05:56.000 --> 00:05:58.000
[Guest]: So I started as a trainee with a

00:05:58.000 --> 00:06:00.000
[Guest]: stipend of 600 rupees a month

00:06:00.000 --> 00:06:02.000
[Guest]: and it was fascinating

00:06:02.000 --> 00:06:04.000
[Guest]: that it was a completely new paper then

00:06:04.000 --> 00:06:06.000
[Guest]: that would become a late motive

00:06:06.000 --> 00:06:08.000
[Guest]: for all of the rest of

00:06:08.000 --> 00:06:10.000
[Guest]: my career because I would have always

00:06:10.000 --> 00:06:12.000
[Guest]: worked with one year exception.

00:06:12.000 --> 00:06:14.000
[Guest]: I always worked in places which were either starting up

00:06:14.000 --> 00:06:16.000
[Guest]: or were already there but

00:06:16.000 --> 00:06:18.000
[Guest]: were going through a complete rejuvenation

00:06:18.000 --> 00:06:20.000
[Guest]: or a complete revamp of some kind

00:06:20.000 --> 00:06:22.000
[Guest]: and that's when you actually

00:06:22.000 --> 00:06:24.000
[Guest]: learn the innards of a process or

00:06:24.000 --> 00:06:26.000
[Guest]: a profession or of a system because

00:06:26.000 --> 00:06:28.000
[Guest]: you can see things being put together or being

00:06:28.000 --> 00:06:30.000
[Guest]: pulled apart. If you always work in places

00:06:30.000 --> 00:06:32.000
[Guest]: that are completely settled

00:06:32.000 --> 00:06:34.000
[Guest]: your pace of learning is much much lower.

00:06:34.000 --> 00:06:36.000
[Guest]: So yeah, I started

00:06:36.000 --> 00:06:38.000
[Guest]: at Newstime in Hyderabad

00:06:38.000 --> 00:06:40.000
[Guest]: then I was with India Today in

00:06:40.000 --> 00:06:42.000
[Guest]: Delhi for a year

00:06:42.000 --> 00:06:44.000
[Guest]: then I joined Economic Times

00:06:44.000 --> 00:06:46.000
[Guest]: where I was features editor when I left

00:06:46.000 --> 00:06:48.000
[Guest]: in 1991

00:06:48.000 --> 00:06:50.000
[Guest]: then I was with Business Standard from 1991

00:06:50.000 --> 00:06:52.000
[Guest]: till

00:06:52.000 --> 00:06:54.000
[Guest]: 1998 I think

00:06:54.000 --> 00:06:56.000
[Guest]: and then I was with Business

00:06:56.000 --> 00:06:58.000
[Guest]: World as editor

00:06:58.000 --> 00:07:00.000
[Guest]: for about 8 years in all

00:07:00.000 --> 00:07:02.000
[Amit Varma]: with a break in between. So you know

00:07:02.000 --> 00:07:04.000
[Amit Varma]: a young journalist starting out today has

00:07:04.000 --> 00:07:06.000
[Amit Varma]: the advantage of the internet, he can read the best

00:07:06.000 --> 00:07:08.000
[Amit Varma]: journalism in the world, he can see back issues

00:07:08.000 --> 00:07:10.000
[Amit Varma]: of the New Yorker, the New York Times, whatever

00:07:10.000 --> 00:07:12.000
[Amit Varma]: but back then when you were starting out in the

00:07:12.000 --> 00:07:14.000
[Amit Varma]: 80s, who were sort

00:07:14.000 --> 00:07:16.000
[Amit Varma]: of your journalistic models and

00:07:16.000 --> 00:07:18.000
[Amit Varma]: how did your ideas of best practices

00:07:18.000 --> 00:07:20.000
[Amit Varma]: and what benchmarks to aim for

00:07:20.000 --> 00:07:22.000
[Amit Varma]: evolve over time, like who were

00:07:22.000 --> 00:07:24.000
[Amit Varma]: your early heroes for example and how did

00:07:24.000 --> 00:07:26.000
[Guest]: that change? When I joined

00:07:26.000 --> 00:07:28.000
[Guest]: India Today at that point of time in

00:07:28.000 --> 00:07:30.000
[Guest]: 1987, I mean at that

00:07:30.000 --> 00:07:32.000
[Guest]: point of time that is the most highly

00:07:32.000 --> 00:07:34.000
[Guest]: valued, it's the most

00:07:34.000 --> 00:07:36.000
[Amit Varma]: important news

00:07:36.000 --> 00:07:38.000
[Guest]: magazine at that point of time

00:07:38.000 --> 00:07:40.000
[Guest]: and had made a large impact and a very good team

00:07:40.000 --> 00:07:42.000
[Guest]: and I was starting out

00:07:42.000 --> 00:07:44.000
[Guest]: as a copy editor on their team

00:07:44.000 --> 00:07:46.000
[Guest]: and it was a very good place to be to learn

00:07:46.000 --> 00:07:48.000
[Guest]: from the rest of the team as well

00:07:48.000 --> 00:07:50.000
[Guest]: When you were in economic

00:07:50.000 --> 00:07:52.000
[Guest]: times, you again

00:07:52.000 --> 00:07:54.000
[Guest]: that was a period when you are starting out

00:07:54.000 --> 00:07:56.000
[Guest]: when you were learning to

00:07:56.000 --> 00:07:58.000
[Guest]: change this place from inside out

00:07:58.000 --> 00:08:00.000
[Guest]: because you are starting your features

00:08:00.000 --> 00:08:02.000
[Guest]: pages in a newspaper that had

00:08:02.000 --> 00:08:04.000
[Guest]: never, forget about features, they had never even

00:08:04.000 --> 00:08:06.000
[Guest]: new, worked on

00:08:06.000 --> 00:08:08.000
[Guest]: anchor news or anything

00:08:08.000 --> 00:08:10.000
[Guest]: other than just essentially plain vanilla

00:08:10.000 --> 00:08:12.000
[Guest]: news stories that

00:08:12.000 --> 00:08:14.000
[Guest]: mostly come out of government announcements

00:08:14.000 --> 00:08:16.000
[Guest]: So working with staff

00:08:16.000 --> 00:08:18.000
[Guest]: who had been in that kind

00:08:18.000 --> 00:08:20.000
[Guest]: of an environment with the same staff

00:08:20.000 --> 00:08:22.000
[Guest]: and to try and bring out

00:08:22.000 --> 00:08:24.000
[Guest]: completely new, those were learning, so I think

00:08:24.000 --> 00:08:26.000
[Guest]: these were periods when you are learning from your

00:08:26.000 --> 00:08:28.000
[Guest]: peers, your bosses

00:08:28.000 --> 00:08:30.000
[Guest]: and what you are doing yourself

00:08:30.000 --> 00:08:32.000
[Guest]: All that changed when I was

00:08:32.000 --> 00:08:34.000
[Guest]: in business standard, when you are starting those

00:08:34.000 --> 00:08:36.000
[Guest]: sections, because that's when

00:08:36.000 --> 00:08:38.000
[Guest]: you realize that each of those sections when you

00:08:38.000 --> 00:08:40.000
[Guest]: went into, you did not have models

00:08:40.000 --> 00:08:42.000
[Guest]: which you could

00:08:42.000 --> 00:08:44.000
[Guest]: pick from anywhere in the country

00:08:44.000 --> 00:08:46.000
[Guest]: because nobody was doing anything

00:08:46.000 --> 00:08:48.000
[Guest]: of that quality that you could say

00:08:48.000 --> 00:08:50.000
[Guest]: I want to beat that or I want to

00:08:50.000 --> 00:08:52.000
[Guest]: You first had to look at

00:08:52.000 --> 00:08:54.000
[Guest]: the best models in the

00:08:54.000 --> 00:08:56.000
[Guest]: world and then look at what

00:08:56.000 --> 00:08:58.000
[Guest]: trade-offs did they make

00:08:58.000 --> 00:09:00.000
[Guest]: that you don't want to make and what different kind of

00:09:00.000 --> 00:09:02.000
[Guest]: trade-offs do you want to make for the audience

00:09:02.000 --> 00:09:04.000
[Guest]: and the market that you are in

00:09:04.000 --> 00:09:06.000
[Guest]: So if you are looking at stock markets, for example, you will look

00:09:06.000 --> 00:09:08.000
[Guest]: at Barron's, you will look at many other

00:09:08.000 --> 00:09:10.000
[Guest]: publications, like if you are looking at

00:09:10.000 --> 00:09:12.000
[Guest]: building the Strategist

00:09:12.000 --> 00:09:14.000
[Guest]: the Harvard Business Review

00:09:14.000 --> 00:09:16.000
[Guest]: and the McKinsey Quarterly, so there are a whole range

00:09:16.000 --> 00:09:18.000
[Guest]: and the management books that are globally

00:09:18.000 --> 00:09:20.000
[Guest]: well accepted

00:09:20.000 --> 00:09:22.000
[Guest]: So in each of those areas that we got into

00:09:22.000 --> 00:09:24.000
[Guest]: this was when it

00:09:24.000 --> 00:09:26.000
[Guest]: became clear or

00:09:26.000 --> 00:09:28.000
[Guest]: really clear that your benchmarks have

00:09:28.000 --> 00:09:30.000
[Guest]: got to be global

00:09:30.000 --> 00:09:32.000
[Guest]: and since then it has been like that

00:09:32.000 --> 00:09:34.000
[Guest]: to answer, since I have been in

00:09:34.000 --> 00:09:36.000
[Guest]: multiple areas all the time

00:09:36.000 --> 00:09:38.000
[Guest]: I would stay with the

00:09:38.000 --> 00:09:40.000
[Guest]: Smart Investor for about six months

00:09:40.000 --> 00:09:42.000
[Guest]: start the team and then move on

00:09:42.000 --> 00:09:44.000
[Guest]: to starting the next section which is

00:09:44.000 --> 00:09:46.000
[Guest]: the Strategist, which is management, again build

00:09:46.000 --> 00:09:48.000
[Guest]: the team and then move on. So what you

00:09:48.000 --> 00:09:50.000
[Guest]: were considering as your competition or

00:09:50.000 --> 00:09:52.000
[Guest]: model to beat depends on which areas

00:09:52.000 --> 00:09:54.000
[Guest]: that you are in. And when did

00:09:54.000 --> 00:09:56.000
[Guest]: you move on from journalism?

00:09:56.000 --> 00:09:58.000
[Guest]: You know the entrepreneurship bug bit me

00:09:58.000 --> 00:10:00.000
[Guest]: at some point of time and I was looking

00:10:00.000 --> 00:10:02.000
[Guest]: at for a way of building something

00:10:02.000 --> 00:10:04.000
[Guest]: that is related to media

00:10:04.000 --> 00:10:06.000
[Guest]: and in around 2001

00:10:06.000 --> 00:10:08.000
[Guest]: we did start a company

00:10:08.000 --> 00:10:10.000
[Guest]: I co-founded a company with two, three

00:10:10.000 --> 00:10:12.000
[Guest]: others which would work with media

00:10:12.000 --> 00:10:14.000
[Guest]: companies abroad

00:10:14.000 --> 00:10:16.000
[Guest]: to create, edit

00:10:16.000 --> 00:10:18.000
[Guest]: and design their products

00:10:18.000 --> 00:10:20.000
[Guest]: but I mean things didn't work out exactly

00:10:20.000 --> 00:10:22.000
[Guest]: the way that we planned because the market

00:10:22.000 --> 00:10:24.000
[Guest]: collapsed, media, print media

00:10:24.000 --> 00:10:26.000
[Guest]: especially in the West

00:10:26.000 --> 00:10:28.000
[Guest]: went through the kind of

00:10:28.000 --> 00:10:30.000
[Guest]: radical destruction of value that

00:10:30.000 --> 00:10:32.000
[Guest]: we have rarely seen in any industry

00:10:32.000 --> 00:10:34.000
[Guest]: so they themselves

00:10:34.000 --> 00:10:36.000
[Guest]: removed most of their editing staff

00:10:36.000 --> 00:10:38.000
[Guest]: so many of the work

00:10:38.000 --> 00:10:40.000
[Guest]: that we were planning to get became

00:10:40.000 --> 00:10:42.000
[Guest]: our assumptions became

00:10:42.000 --> 00:10:44.000
[Guest]: untenable

00:10:44.000 --> 00:10:46.000
[Guest]: but you could say this was an

00:10:46.000 --> 00:10:48.000
[Guest]: entrepreneurial break or a

00:10:48.000 --> 00:10:50.000
[Guest]: period but it was still related

00:10:50.000 --> 00:10:52.000
[Guest]: to media and not

00:10:52.000 --> 00:10:54.000
[Amit Varma]: outside of it. And sort of

00:10:54.000 --> 00:10:56.000
[Amit Varma]: coming to your book now, kind of

00:10:56.000 --> 00:10:58.000
[Amit Varma]: early Indians, how did you

00:10:58.000 --> 00:11:00.000
[Amit Varma]: start getting interested in this subject?

00:11:00.000 --> 00:11:02.000
[Guest]: I have always been

00:11:02.000 --> 00:11:04.000
[Guest]: interested. It's not that

00:11:04.000 --> 00:11:06.000
[Guest]: I had a greater interest in history per se

00:11:06.000 --> 00:11:08.000
[Guest]: but pre-history

00:11:08.000 --> 00:11:10.000
[Guest]: for some odd reason which I still

00:11:10.000 --> 00:11:12.000
[Guest]: can't fully understand

00:11:12.000 --> 00:11:14.000
[Guest]: the Harappan civilization for example

00:11:14.000 --> 00:11:16.000
[Guest]: has always had a

00:11:16.000 --> 00:11:18.000
[Guest]: great hold on me and

00:11:18.000 --> 00:11:20.000
[Guest]: ever since I came across it

00:11:20.000 --> 00:11:22.000
[Guest]: and these were also things that

00:11:22.000 --> 00:11:24.000
[Guest]: because this is not about chronology

00:11:24.000 --> 00:11:26.000
[Guest]: who did what because the very

00:11:26.000 --> 00:11:28.000
[Guest]: fact that you cannot know the names of the people

00:11:28.000 --> 00:11:30.000
[Guest]: in pre-history because there are no documents or the places

00:11:30.000 --> 00:11:32.000
[Amit Varma]: I mean the definition of pre-history is before

00:11:32.000 --> 00:11:34.000
[Guest]: writing starts

00:11:34.000 --> 00:11:36.000
[Guest]: and therefore you are dealing

00:11:36.000 --> 00:11:38.000
[Guest]: with actual issues because to me

00:11:38.000 --> 00:11:40.000
[Guest]: what is frustrating in history

00:11:40.000 --> 00:11:42.000
[Guest]: is that there are too many people and too many

00:11:42.000 --> 00:11:44.000
[Guest]: specific

00:11:44.000 --> 00:11:46.000
[Guest]: issues and specific concerns

00:11:46.000 --> 00:11:48.000
[Guest]: and in pre-history when you don't have any of

00:11:48.000 --> 00:11:50.000
[Guest]: those things you are dealing with pure issues

00:11:50.000 --> 00:11:52.000
[Guest]: it's not talking about

00:11:52.000 --> 00:11:54.000
[Guest]: perspectives it's about what

00:11:54.000 --> 00:11:56.000
[Guest]: really happened here so some of the

00:11:56.000 --> 00:11:58.000
[Guest]: questions that were on my mind which has always

00:11:58.000 --> 00:12:00.000
[Guest]: been the case is who were the Harappans

00:12:00.000 --> 00:12:02.000
[Guest]: where did they come from where did they go

00:12:02.000 --> 00:12:04.000
[Guest]: and

00:12:04.000 --> 00:12:06.000
[Guest]: why did it take more than a thousand

00:12:06.000 --> 00:12:08.000
[Guest]: years imagine this more than a thousand years

00:12:08.000 --> 00:12:10.000
[Guest]: for cities

00:12:10.000 --> 00:12:12.000
[Guest]: and urbanism itself to rise up

00:12:12.000 --> 00:12:14.000
[Guest]: again in the subcontinent

00:12:14.000 --> 00:12:16.000
[Guest]: it strikes you if you haven't

00:12:16.000 --> 00:12:18.000
[Guest]: been to Dhaulavira in Gujarat please go

00:12:18.000 --> 00:12:20.000
[Guest]: one day it's one of the

00:12:20.000 --> 00:12:22.000
[Guest]: major Harappan centres

00:12:22.000 --> 00:12:24.000
[Guest]: the most distinctive Harappan

00:12:24.000 --> 00:12:26.000
[Guest]: city in India today

00:12:26.000 --> 00:12:28.000
[Guest]: and it's a

00:12:28.000 --> 00:12:30.000
[Guest]: stunning sight you know most of the

00:12:30.000 --> 00:12:32.000
[Guest]: superstructure has already been destroyed so you

00:12:32.000 --> 00:12:34.000
[Guest]: can only see the substructure

00:12:34.000 --> 00:12:36.000
[Guest]: the foundations but even

00:12:36.000 --> 00:12:38.000
[Guest]: seeing that you can see the robustness

00:12:38.000 --> 00:12:40.000
[Guest]: with which these places

00:12:40.000 --> 00:12:42.000
[Guest]: were built and you should see

00:12:42.000 --> 00:12:44.000
[Guest]: the scale of the ambition you know

00:12:44.000 --> 00:12:46.000
[Guest]: there's a large stadium

00:12:46.000 --> 00:12:48.000
[Guest]: stands for people and you can imagine

00:12:48.000 --> 00:12:50.000
[Guest]: what could have been going on there

00:12:50.000 --> 00:12:52.000
[Guest]: just that scale of ambition

00:12:52.000 --> 00:12:54.000
[Guest]: and the sturdiness with which things

00:12:54.000 --> 00:12:56.000
[Guest]: are built the huge reservoirs that have

00:12:56.000 --> 00:12:58.000
[Guest]: built and

00:12:58.000 --> 00:13:00.000
[Guest]: then you realize that

00:13:00.000 --> 00:13:02.000
[Guest]: this was would have been around 2600

00:13:02.000 --> 00:13:04.000
[Guest]: BCE

00:13:04.000 --> 00:13:06.000
[Guest]: and you have to wait till the Mauryans

00:13:06.000 --> 00:13:08.000
[Guest]: arrive you know

00:13:08.000 --> 00:13:10.000
[Guest]: nearly a thousand five hundred years later

00:13:10.000 --> 00:13:12.000
[Guest]: to see structures

00:13:12.000 --> 00:13:14.000
[Guest]: of that scale ambition

00:13:14.000 --> 00:13:16.000
[Guest]: again so these were questions

00:13:16.000 --> 00:13:18.000
[Guest]: that did not have good answers to

00:13:18.000 --> 00:13:20.000
[Guest]: they were suppositions

00:13:20.000 --> 00:13:22.000
[Guest]: so around six years ago

00:13:22.000 --> 00:13:24.000
[Guest]: I decided that it would make sense

00:13:24.000 --> 00:13:26.000
[Guest]: to try and look at the Harappan

00:13:26.000 --> 00:13:28.000
[Guest]: questions in detail and see where

00:13:28.000 --> 00:13:30.000
[Guest]: we are compared to where we were then

00:13:30.000 --> 00:13:32.000
[Guest]: and what all the

00:13:32.000 --> 00:13:34.000
[Guest]: relevant disciplines today based on

00:13:34.000 --> 00:13:36.000
[Guest]: current research has to say

00:13:36.000 --> 00:13:38.000
[Guest]: on the equation I thought I would be able to write a big

00:13:38.000 --> 00:13:40.000
[Guest]: story or a cover story

00:13:40.000 --> 00:13:42.000
[Guest]: somewhere on the Harappans

00:13:42.000 --> 00:13:44.000
[Guest]: and I started going to all these

00:13:44.000 --> 00:13:46.000
[Guest]: sites, Tholavira,

00:13:46.000 --> 00:13:48.000
[Guest]: Lothal in Gujarat, Rakhigarhi

00:13:48.000 --> 00:13:50.000
[Amit Varma]: in Haryana. How did it feel to see all these

00:13:50.000 --> 00:13:52.000
[Amit Varma]: places because to someone who is not aware of the context

00:13:52.000 --> 00:13:54.000
[Amit Varma]: or the history it will just be ancient ruins

00:13:54.000 --> 00:13:56.000
[Amit Varma]: or whatever but you are actually

00:13:56.000 --> 00:13:58.000
[Amit Varma]: going there with a sense of what it was

00:13:58.000 --> 00:14:00.000
[Amit Varma]: and what the ambition behind it was and how old

00:14:00.000 --> 00:14:02.000
[Amit Varma]: it all is. That's right. And how was

00:14:02.000 --> 00:14:04.000
[Guest]: the experience? Oh it's absolutely stunning

00:14:04.000 --> 00:14:06.000
[Guest]: and the visit to Tholavira

00:14:06.000 --> 00:14:08.000
[Guest]: I would say of all the places

00:14:08.000 --> 00:14:10.000
[Guest]: I have visited a lot of places I have been to

00:14:10.000 --> 00:14:12.000
[Guest]: other prehistoric places in India

00:14:12.000 --> 00:14:14.000
[Guest]: which are not related to the Harappans

00:14:14.000 --> 00:14:16.000
[Guest]: but that happened later

00:14:16.000 --> 00:14:18.000
[Guest]: but the visit to Tholavira was

00:14:18.000 --> 00:14:20.000
[Guest]: really moving because

00:14:20.000 --> 00:14:22.000
[Guest]: at that point of time

00:14:22.000 --> 00:14:24.000
[Guest]: it was not yet when I visited it was not yet

00:14:24.000 --> 00:14:26.000
[Guest]: fully clear are these

00:14:26.000 --> 00:14:28.000
[Guest]: people our ancestors or

00:14:28.000 --> 00:14:30.000
[Guest]: did they people who came from somewhere and disappeared

00:14:30.000 --> 00:14:32.000
[Guest]: now we know of course that they are

00:14:32.000 --> 00:14:34.000
[Guest]: to stand there and see the work

00:14:34.000 --> 00:14:36.000
[Guest]: that had been done and

00:14:36.000 --> 00:14:38.000
[Guest]: the streets that had been laid out

00:14:38.000 --> 00:14:40.000
[Guest]: because you can see the streets right

00:14:40.000 --> 00:14:42.000
[Guest]: and when you can see the streets you can almost

00:14:42.000 --> 00:14:44.000
[Guest]: see even though they are not there you can

00:14:44.000 --> 00:14:46.000
[Guest]: almost see the people walking down there

00:14:46.000 --> 00:14:48.000
[Guest]: visually it projects itself onto your mind

00:14:48.000 --> 00:14:50.000
[Guest]: so it was a very very moving

00:14:50.000 --> 00:14:52.000
[Guest]: experience. Lothal is a port city

00:14:52.000 --> 00:14:54.000
[Guest]: and yeah

00:14:54.000 --> 00:14:56.000
[Guest]: it also is much smaller than Tholavira

00:14:56.000 --> 00:14:58.000
[Guest]: but a stunning one. Rakhigarhi

00:14:58.000 --> 00:15:00.000
[Guest]: there is nothing much to see

00:15:00.000 --> 00:15:02.000
[Guest]: because whatever has been excavated

00:15:02.000 --> 00:15:04.000
[Guest]: they haven't they have filled it up again

00:15:04.000 --> 00:15:06.000
[Guest]: and to preserve it I think

00:15:06.000 --> 00:15:08.000
[Guest]: but there is nothing much to see

00:15:08.000 --> 00:15:10.000
[Guest]: but it is still interesting to

00:15:10.000 --> 00:15:12.000
[Guest]: go there and imagine that this

00:15:12.000 --> 00:15:14.000
[Guest]: place there used to be a thriving

00:15:14.000 --> 00:15:16.000
[Guest]: civilization the best of its time

00:15:16.000 --> 00:15:18.000
[Amit Varma]: and the interesting thing is you said

00:15:18.000 --> 00:15:20.000
[Amit Varma]: that you sort of got interested

00:15:20.000 --> 00:15:22.000
[Amit Varma]: in this again about you know 6-7 years

00:15:22.000 --> 00:15:24.000
[Amit Varma]: ago and that's around the time

00:15:24.000 --> 00:15:26.000
[Amit Varma]: that the science was also evolving

00:15:26.000 --> 00:15:28.000
[Amit Varma]: at a rapid pace

00:15:28.000 --> 00:15:30.000
[Amit Varma]: in fact if I may quote from your book

00:15:30.000 --> 00:15:32.000
[Amit Varma]: quote just to get a sense of the speed

00:15:32.000 --> 00:15:34.000
[Amit Varma]: at which things have moved consider this

00:15:34.000 --> 00:15:36.000
[Amit Varma]: when work on this book began 6 years ago

00:15:36.000 --> 00:15:38.000
[Amit Varma]: we did not know who were the people of the Harappan

00:15:38.000 --> 00:15:40.000
[Amit Varma]: civilization or where their

00:15:40.000 --> 00:15:42.000
[Amit Varma]: descendants had gone but now

00:15:42.000 --> 00:15:44.000
[Amit Varma]: we do. 6 years ago we did not know

00:15:44.000 --> 00:15:46.000
[Amit Varma]: how much of our ancestry we owed to the

00:15:46.000 --> 00:15:48.000
[Amit Varma]: original out of Africa migrants who reached

00:15:48.000 --> 00:15:50.000
[Amit Varma]: India about 65,000 years ago

00:15:50.000 --> 00:15:52.000
[Amit Varma]: but now we do. 6 years

00:15:52.000 --> 00:15:54.000
[Amit Varma]: ago we did not know when the caste system

00:15:54.000 --> 00:15:56.000
[Amit Varma]: began but now we can zero in on the

00:15:56.000 --> 00:15:58.000
[Amit Varma]: period with a fair degree of genetic accuracy

00:15:58.000 --> 00:16:00.000
[Amit Varma]: these are just a few examples that

00:16:00.000 --> 00:16:02.000
[Amit Varma]: demonstrate our rapidly improving understanding

00:16:02.000 --> 00:16:04.000
[Amit Varma]: of prehistory and not just with regard to India

00:16:04.000 --> 00:16:06.000
[Amit Varma]: stop quote and

00:16:06.000 --> 00:16:08.000
[Amit Varma]: what you go on to describe in the pages

00:16:08.000 --> 00:16:10.000
[Amit Varma]: of your book and I urge all the listeners to read

00:16:10.000 --> 00:16:12.000
[Amit Varma]: it for themselves but what you go on to

00:16:12.000 --> 00:16:14.000
[Amit Varma]: describe is a

00:16:14.000 --> 00:16:16.000
[Amit Varma]: sort of a revolution in the science

00:16:16.000 --> 00:16:18.000
[Amit Varma]: not just in like one field

00:16:18.000 --> 00:16:20.000
[Amit Varma]: of it but you have looked at like

00:16:20.000 --> 00:16:22.000
[Amit Varma]: 6 or 7 different disciplines

00:16:22.000 --> 00:16:24.000
[Amit Varma]: here to kind of come to the conclusions

00:16:24.000 --> 00:16:26.000
[Amit Varma]: but that you've come to which is

00:16:26.000 --> 00:16:28.000
[Amit Varma]: now the new evolved understanding of what

00:16:28.000 --> 00:16:30.000
[Amit Varma]: exactly happened and I

00:16:30.000 --> 00:16:32.000
[Amit Varma]: had absolutely no idea all of this has happened

00:16:32.000 --> 00:16:34.000
[Amit Varma]: till I read your book to be honest so tell

00:16:34.000 --> 00:16:36.000
[Amit Varma]: me a little bit about what has happened in the

00:16:36.000 --> 00:16:38.000
[Guest]: science. Yeah when I started on this

00:16:38.000 --> 00:16:40.000
[Guest]: 6 years ago I wasn't

00:16:40.000 --> 00:16:42.000
[Guest]: aware of the revolution that is

00:16:42.000 --> 00:16:44.000
[Guest]: happening with population genetics I wasn't

00:16:44.000 --> 00:16:46.000
[Guest]: I was barely conscious of the fact that there

00:16:46.000 --> 00:16:48.000
[Guest]: is something called population genetics

00:16:48.000 --> 00:16:50.000
[Guest]: that might be relevant to the

00:16:50.000 --> 00:16:52.000
[Guest]: area that you're looking at I was

00:16:52.000 --> 00:16:54.000
[Guest]: going through sites I was talking to archaeologists

00:16:54.000 --> 00:16:56.000
[Guest]: who had excavated them I was talking to

00:16:56.000 --> 00:16:58.000
[Guest]: historians I was talking to epigraphists who

00:16:58.000 --> 00:17:00.000
[Guest]: had looked at the script

00:17:00.000 --> 00:17:02.000
[Guest]: talking to philologists who might have

00:17:02.000 --> 00:17:04.000
[Guest]: something to say about what the old texts have

00:17:04.000 --> 00:17:06.000
[Guest]: to say about these things

00:17:06.000 --> 00:17:08.000
[Guest]: so I was going through

00:17:08.000 --> 00:17:10.000
[Guest]: all the traditional disciplines which

00:17:10.000 --> 00:17:12.000
[Guest]: they themselves had

00:17:12.000 --> 00:17:14.000
[Guest]: progressed during the last few decades

00:17:14.000 --> 00:17:16.000
[Guest]: that one had not been following it

00:17:16.000 --> 00:17:18.000
[Guest]: so it was quite interesting

00:17:18.000 --> 00:17:20.000
[Guest]: to see how far we had come and

00:17:20.000 --> 00:17:22.000
[Guest]: so it's only about 2-3 years into the

00:17:22.000 --> 00:17:24.000
[Guest]: research then you start

00:17:24.000 --> 00:17:26.000
[Guest]: understanding that hey

00:17:26.000 --> 00:17:28.000
[Guest]: a lot of new interesting information is coming

00:17:28.000 --> 00:17:30.000
[Guest]: from a new field that you had not been focused on

00:17:30.000 --> 00:17:32.000
[Guest]: which is called population genetics

00:17:32.000 --> 00:17:34.000
[Guest]: and they were using understanding

00:17:34.000 --> 00:17:36.000
[Guest]: of the genome of present day populations

00:17:36.000 --> 00:17:38.000
[Guest]: mostly initially

00:17:38.000 --> 00:17:40.000
[Guest]: to work out affinities between

00:17:40.000 --> 00:17:42.000
[Guest]: different population groups

00:17:42.000 --> 00:17:44.000
[Guest]: and that is absolutely interesting to the

00:17:44.000 --> 00:17:46.000
[Guest]: question of who were the harapins

00:17:46.000 --> 00:17:48.000
[Guest]: so then I started reading in the

00:17:48.000 --> 00:17:50.000
[Guest]: papers and getting in touch with the

00:17:50.000 --> 00:17:52.000
[Guest]: world's leading experts

00:17:52.000 --> 00:17:54.000
[Guest]: in India and outside

00:17:54.000 --> 00:17:56.000
[Guest]: and discussing with them

00:17:56.000 --> 00:17:58.000
[Guest]: their work and what they were finding

00:17:58.000 --> 00:18:00.000
[Guest]: and how it has been changing

00:18:00.000 --> 00:18:02.000
[Guest]: and during this process what you realized

00:18:02.000 --> 00:18:04.000
[Guest]: also is that population

00:18:04.000 --> 00:18:06.000
[Guest]: genetics itself is a

00:18:06.000 --> 00:18:08.000
[Guest]: science that is proceeding

00:18:08.000 --> 00:18:10.000
[Guest]: at a very fast rate

00:18:10.000 --> 00:18:12.000
[Guest]: it's progressing, it is introducing

00:18:12.000 --> 00:18:14.000
[Guest]: new ways of analyzing

00:18:14.000 --> 00:18:16.000
[Amit Varma]: and the cost of doing

00:18:16.000 --> 00:18:18.000
[Amit Varma]: It almost seems like it's not incremental

00:18:18.000 --> 00:18:20.000
[Guest]: it's exponential, that's how it felt to me

00:18:20.000 --> 00:18:22.000
[Guest]: I think all disciplines go through that at some point

00:18:22.000 --> 00:18:24.000
[Amit Varma]: in their lifetime, maybe automotive

00:18:24.000 --> 00:18:26.000
[Guest]: technology does that, then it stabilizes

00:18:26.000 --> 00:18:28.000
[Guest]: I think all disciplines in their

00:18:28.000 --> 00:18:30.000
[Guest]: life has a period when it is

00:18:30.000 --> 00:18:32.000
[Guest]: ramping up very rapidly

00:18:32.000 --> 00:18:34.000
[Guest]: in terms of its understanding

00:18:34.000 --> 00:18:36.000
[Guest]: and tools that it uses

00:18:36.000 --> 00:18:38.000
[Guest]: so population genetics went through that phase

00:18:38.000 --> 00:18:40.000
[Guest]: in the last 4-5 years

00:18:40.000 --> 00:18:42.000
[Guest]: so and

00:18:42.000 --> 00:18:44.000
[Guest]: then in the last 2-3 years

00:18:44.000 --> 00:18:46.000
[Guest]: what has happened is that they started

00:18:46.000 --> 00:18:48.000
[Guest]: using ancient DNA

00:18:48.000 --> 00:18:50.000
[Guest]: that is DNA from people who lived

00:18:50.000 --> 00:18:52.000
[Guest]: thousands or tens of thousands of years ago

00:18:52.000 --> 00:18:54.000
[Guest]: and then

00:18:54.000 --> 00:18:56.000
[Guest]: the whole game changed

00:18:56.000 --> 00:18:58.000
[Guest]: because now you can not only understand

00:18:58.000 --> 00:19:00.000
[Guest]: affinities between populations

00:19:00.000 --> 00:19:02.000
[Guest]: now you can answer the question who moved

00:19:02.000 --> 00:19:04.000
[Guest]: where and when

00:19:04.000 --> 00:19:06.000
[Guest]: and that is dramatic right

00:19:06.000 --> 00:19:08.000
[Guest]: because that answers

00:19:08.000 --> 00:19:10.000
[Guest]: the most basic questions

00:19:10.000 --> 00:19:12.000
[Guest]: about prehistory of people

00:19:12.000 --> 00:19:14.000
[Guest]: movements that formed populations

00:19:14.000 --> 00:19:16.000
[Guest]: and these have answered questions

00:19:16.000 --> 00:19:18.000
[Guest]: not just in South Asia, they have answered

00:19:18.000 --> 00:19:20.000
[Guest]: questions of population formation in

