[Amit Varma]: to be our next stop. But before we come there through all this

00:25:54.000 --> 00:25:56.000
[Amit Varma]: time, how were these human migrations

00:25:56.000 --> 00:25:58.000
[Amit Varma]: and the evolution

00:25:58.000 --> 00:26:00.000
[Amit Varma]: and the dominance of homo sapiens affected by

00:26:00.000 --> 00:26:02.000
[Amit Varma]: things like geography and geology and weather?

00:26:02.000 --> 00:26:04.000
[Guest]: Very very significantly. I

00:26:04.000 --> 00:26:06.000
[Guest]: think since when we

00:26:06.000 --> 00:26:08.000
[Guest]: talk about tree history we are talking about

00:26:08.000 --> 00:26:10.000
[Guest]: such large spans of

00:26:10.000 --> 00:26:12.000
[Guest]: time. And we

00:26:12.000 --> 00:26:14.000
[Guest]: are usually used to speaking about

00:26:14.000 --> 00:26:16.000
[Guest]: decades or centuries

00:26:16.000 --> 00:26:18.000
[Guest]: etc. In which case

00:26:18.000 --> 00:26:20.000
[Guest]: climates and these don't change

00:26:20.000 --> 00:26:22.000
[Guest]: all that much. So this

00:26:22.000 --> 00:26:24.000
[Guest]: is a radical shift that takes place when you are

00:26:24.000 --> 00:26:26.000
[Guest]: discussing tree history that you have to

00:26:26.000 --> 00:26:28.000
[Guest]: because that's a predominant

00:26:28.000 --> 00:26:30.000
[Guest]: formation of and affects human

00:26:30.000 --> 00:26:32.000
[Guest]: behaviour. For example

00:26:32.000 --> 00:26:34.000
[Guest]: when many of the

00:26:34.000 --> 00:26:36.000
[Guest]: population movements, how do

00:26:36.000 --> 00:26:38.000
[Guest]: humans or even

00:26:38.000 --> 00:26:40.000
[Guest]: animals or mammals move from one

00:26:40.000 --> 00:26:42.000
[Guest]: place to another? What is it that

00:26:42.000 --> 00:26:44.000
[Guest]: drives it? One of the things that

00:26:44.000 --> 00:26:46.000
[Guest]: drives it is

00:26:46.000 --> 00:26:48.000
[Guest]: you know dramatic climate changes.

00:26:48.000 --> 00:26:50.000
[Guest]: During the glacial ages

00:26:50.000 --> 00:26:52.000
[Guest]: since almost all of the water

00:26:52.000 --> 00:26:54.000
[Guest]: is locked up in ice

00:26:54.000 --> 00:26:56.000
[Guest]: sheets, there is very little

00:26:56.000 --> 00:26:58.000
[Guest]: evaporation, much less evaporation happening

00:26:58.000 --> 00:27:00.000
[Guest]: and so glacial ages are very arid.

00:27:00.000 --> 00:27:02.000
[Guest]: So quite apart from the fact that

00:27:02.000 --> 00:27:04.000
[Guest]: a lot of the world will be

00:27:04.000 --> 00:27:06.000
[Guest]: covered in ice sheets, even other parts

00:27:06.000 --> 00:27:08.000
[Guest]: that are not covered in ice sheets, there

00:27:08.000 --> 00:27:10.000
[Guest]: is a very great aridity. So

00:27:10.000 --> 00:27:12.000
[Guest]: places that would have been earlier

00:27:12.000 --> 00:27:14.000
[Guest]: luxurious and thriving with life

00:27:14.000 --> 00:27:16.000
[Guest]: and greenery would

00:27:16.000 --> 00:27:18.000
[Guest]: go back to being deserts.

00:27:18.000 --> 00:27:20.000
[Guest]: So and when

00:27:20.000 --> 00:27:22.000
[Guest]: warms up again, then you see

00:27:22.000 --> 00:27:24.000
[Guest]: there are new lush pastures where

00:27:24.000 --> 00:27:26.000
[Guest]: there were deserts earlier and

00:27:26.000 --> 00:27:28.000
[Guest]: you would then see animals

00:27:28.000 --> 00:27:30.000
[Guest]: and you know moving in there

00:27:30.000 --> 00:27:32.000
[Guest]: because there is a new territory for them

00:27:32.000 --> 00:27:34.000
[Guest]: and when animals or cattle

00:27:34.000 --> 00:27:36.000
[Guest]: move in, you can also see their predators

00:27:36.000 --> 00:27:38.000
[Guest]: and humans and everybody moves in. That's

00:27:38.000 --> 00:27:40.000
[Guest]: what makes

00:27:40.000 --> 00:27:42.000
[Guest]: one of the earliest historic

00:27:42.000 --> 00:27:44.000
[Guest]: monuments of people or even the out of Africa

00:27:44.000 --> 00:27:46.000
[Guest]: migrations would have been shaped

00:27:46.000 --> 00:27:48.000
[Guest]: by these changes in

00:27:48.000 --> 00:27:50.000
[Guest]: climates in various ways.

00:27:50.000 --> 00:27:52.000
[Guest]: And sometimes it may not be in ways

00:27:52.000 --> 00:27:54.000
[Guest]: that we imagine, it might be in counterintuitive

00:27:54.000 --> 00:27:56.000
[Guest]: ways also because

00:27:56.000 --> 00:27:58.000
[Guest]: if there is greater aridity, it may mean

00:27:58.000 --> 00:28:00.000
[Guest]: they have to move to new areas

00:28:00.000 --> 00:28:02.000
[Guest]: in search of

00:28:02.000 --> 00:28:04.000
[Guest]: food. So

00:28:04.000 --> 00:28:06.000
[Guest]: this has to be taken into account

00:28:06.000 --> 00:28:08.000
[Guest]: when any specific question

00:28:08.000 --> 00:28:10.000
[Guest]: of the prehistoric period is being

00:28:10.000 --> 00:28:12.000
[Guest]: taken into account. And my book talks

00:28:12.000 --> 00:28:14.000
[Guest]: about how around 35,000

00:28:14.000 --> 00:28:16.000
[Guest]: years ago in the Indian

00:28:16.000 --> 00:28:18.000
[Guest]: subcontinent, while there

00:28:18.000 --> 00:28:20.000
[Guest]: is evidence that there is something dramatic happened,

00:28:20.000 --> 00:28:22.000
[Guest]: the climate deteriorated,

00:28:22.000 --> 00:28:24.000
[Guest]: modern humans started using

00:28:24.000 --> 00:28:26.000
[Guest]: because they were in competition with

00:28:26.000 --> 00:28:28.000
[Guest]: the previous would have been for

